Subject: [R-sig-Debian] R memory allocation in Linux
References: <87fwv9upew.fsf@guruji.demimonde>
	<960061.56096.qm@web57301.mail.re1.yahoo.com>
Message-ID: <87bp5wumtv.fsf@guruji.demimonde>

gc() will tell you how much memory you are currently using, and the
maximum amount of memory that you have ever used within the current R
session. It doesn't tell you what the maximum amount of memory available
to your R session is.

So running gc() on a new R session doesn't really tell you anything
useful. Running gc() before you try the operation that fails to allocate
the big vector will tell you how much memory you are using at the point
of failure, which would be more helpful.

Since free shows your 4GB of memory is all accounted for, I think this
is an issue with your R script using too much memory, rather than a
problem with your operating system.


HTH,

Tyler


